class TreeNode {
    constructor(val) {
        this.val = val;
        this.left = this.right = null;
    }
}

function recoverFromPreorder(S) {
    return helper(S, 0);
}

function helper(S, depth) {
    if (!S.length) return null;

    let numDashes = 0;
    let start = 0;
    while (S.charAt(start) === '-') {
        numDashes++;
        start++;
    }

    if (numDashes < depth) return null;

    S = S.substring(start - depth);
    let end = 0;
    while (S.charAt(end) !== '-' && end < S.length) end++;
    const val = parseInt(S.substring(0, end));

    const node = new TreeNode(val);
    S = S.substring(end);

    node.left = helper(S, depth + 1);
    node.right = helper(S, depth + 1);

    return node;
}
```

    The algorithm starts by creating a helper function that operates on the given input string S and current depth (initially 0 for root).

The number of dashes at the current position is counted. If the number of dashes do not equal the depth, it means the current value is not meant for the current node, so we return null. Otherwise, we extract the value and create a new node with that value.

We then call the helper function recursively on the left and right children of the current node with incremented depth. These calls repeat the same process for each subtree.

After consuming the traversal string, the helper function returns the root of the recovered binary tree.

solutionCode.java:
    ```java
class TreeNode {
    int val;
    TreeNode left;
    TreeNode right;
    TreeNode(int x) { val = x; }
}

public TreeNode recoverFromPreorder(String S) {
    return helper(new java.util.Scanner(S), 0);
}

public TreeNode helper(java.util.Scanner scanner, int depth) {
    int numDashes = 0;
    while (scanner.hasNext("-")) {
        numDashes++;
        scanner.next("-");
    }

    if (numDashes != depth) {
        while (numDashes-- > 0) {
            scanner.next("-");
        }
        return null;
    }

    int val = scanner.nextInt();
    TreeNode node = new TreeNode(val);
    node.left = helper(scanner, depth + 1);
    node.right = helper(scanner, depth + 1);
    return node;
}
```

    The algorithm starts by creating a helper function that operates on the given input string S and current depth (initially 0 for root).

The number of dashes at the current position is counted. If the number of dashes do not equal the depth, it means the current value is not meant for the current node, so we return null. Otherwise, we extract the value and create a new node with that value.

We then call the helper function recursively on the left and right children of the current node with incremented depth. These calls repeat the same process for each subtree.

After consuming the traversal string, the helper function returns the root of the recovered binary tree.
